UNITED STATES v. MANGANO. (Circuit Court of Appeals, Eighth Circuit. May 6, 1924.) No. 6371. In Error to the District Court of the United States for the District of Nebraska; Joseph W. Woodrough, Judge. Libel of forfeiture by the United States, wherein Tony Mangano intervened. From an order dismissing the libel, and in favor of Mangano, the United States brings error. Affirmed. George A. Keyser, Asst. U. S. Atty., of Omaha, Neb. (James C. Kinsler, U. S. Atty., of Omaha, Neb., on the brief), for the United States. E. D. O’Sullivan, of Omaha, Neb. (W. N. Jamieson and C. J. Southard, both of Omaha, Neb., on the brief), for defendant in error.

Before LEWIS, Circuit Judge, and BOOTH and STMES, District Judges.

BOOTH, District Judge.

. The facts in this case are substantially the same as in No. 6370, United States, Plaintiff in Error, v. Tony Mangano, Defendant in Error, 299 Fed. 492, and the decision in that case is controlling.

Order affirmed.
